  

<h2 id="antinotes-key-word-super-powers-make-a-real-difference">Antinote‚Äôs key word super powers make a real difference</h2>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_177bc256f0ee469c998e912e20ece048/_image_cache/d3c03a8c-db5d-4d23-8e92-cd0589e54c30.png" alt="Screenshots from Antinote showing the Welcome screen and the paste key word instructions, plus the Antinote logo" width="1322" height="798"> <em>Antinote screenshots by the Author</em></p>
<hr>
<p><em>Edited to add instructions for the Custom <span class="small-caps">URL</span> export option</em></p>
<p>In this review I‚Äôll run through how Antinote works and explain why I like using it on my Mac even though it doesn‚Äôt inherently store data as plain text.</p>
<p>Antinote isn‚Äôt a ground breaking app, but it is great at being an always available scratchpad for text, calculations and conversions. I like the plain text friendly export features and looks.</p>
<p>My first reaction on hearing of Antinote was less than enthusiastic. Nooo thanks, I thought. I‚Äôll pass. It seemed to me it was yet another, less useful iteration of apps like SideNote and Unclutter.</p>
<p>I already have <a href="https://ellanew.com/ptpl/157-2025-05-19-journelly-is-org-for-those-who-dont-do-org">Journelly</a> writing directly into plain text, and <a href="https://ellanew.com/ptpl/056-text-into-obsidian-shortcuts-drafts">Drafts</a> set up to append formatted text to my <a href="https://ellanew.com/2025-04-14-obtf-start-here">One Big Text File</a> (<span class="small-caps">OBTF</span>). I‚Äôm also aware of several other apps and shortcuts that can do likewise. Why would I even look at another option, especially one that locks away my notes in a format I can‚Äôt read with these here human eyes?</p>
<p>It may be lightning fast to start writing in Antinote and easy to export text to other apps but for me the stand out feature is its ability to calculate and convert pretty much anything, and then bring that text into Obsidian.</p>
<p><em><a href="https://antinote.io" target="_blank">Antinote</a> is available with a limited free trial or $5 up front. It‚Äôs also included with a Setapp subscription. 30-day free trial offer below.</em></p>
<h3 id="antinotes-key-word-super-powers">Antinote‚Äôs key word super powers</h3>
<p><span class="small-caps">‚å•A</span> (Option + A) brings up the small Antinote window, neatly on the left hand side of the screen. You can start typing right away, or use one of Antinote‚Äôs key words on the first line of the note to perform special functions. Once typed, key words turn blue and the app tells you what you can do next.</p>
<p>I was pleased to learn that you don‚Äôt need to remember the key words. Type <code>/</code> and you‚Äôll see a list of all eight options. From there you can enter the number beside the keyword you‚Äôre after, or type it in full. A two-finger swipe from right to left takes you through a tutorial of each. I love the humour laced throughout!</p>
<p>Here are the keywords Antinote recognises, and what they do:</p>
<p><strong>math</strong> Calculates sums, allows for variables. Converts currency, weight, length, volume, etc.</p>
<p><strong>sum</strong> Adds all the numbers in the text you write, eg.<span class="push-double"></span> <span class="pull-double">‚Äú</span>I walked&nbsp;.5 km on Monday, 2 km on Wednesday, and 5 km on Friday‚Äù, will return a total of 7.5</p>
<p><strong>avg</strong> Averages all the numbers in the text you write, eg.<span class="push-double"></span> <span class="pull-double">‚Äú</span>I walked&nbsp;.5 km on Monday, 2 km on Wednesday, and 5 km on Friday‚Äù, will return an average of 2.50</p>
<p><strong>list</strong> Every line will be part of a checklist; good for fleeting tasks</p>
<p><strong>count</strong> Counts items, words, characters, and gives a Flesch ease of reading score</p>
<p><strong>code</strong> Syntax highlighting for various coding languages</p>
<p><strong>paste</strong> Paste any screenshot containing text into the app and it will instantly type it out as plain text. (No, Antinote can‚Äôt store graphics. You‚Äôre better off with SideNote, Paste, or Unclutter for that.) It can‚Äôt beat TextSniper and the like, but it does a good enough job for me. In this mode Antinote also will watch your clipboard and paste anything you copy. I‚Äôve been using it to keep a record of the paragraphs I cut from my work during the editing process.</p>
<p><strong>timer</strong> An easy to use timer or stopwatch that works in the background, even while creating more Antinotes. When a timer is up, you‚Äôll be presented with a full screen notification, and a wildlife fact! Cute.</p>
<h3 id="getting-text-out-of-antinote">Getting text out of Antinote</h3>
<p>Antinote already has you covered for fleeting notes, but when you want to get text into your more permanent notes you can ‚Äî</p>
<ul>
<li>Save one or all notes as a&nbsp;.txt or&nbsp;.md file in a location of your choice</li>
<li>Export to the default location in an Obsidian vault</li>
<li>Export to Bear</li>
<li>Export to Apple Notes</li>
<li>Export with a custom <span class="small-caps">URL</span> template</li>
</ul>
<p>At first I set Obsidian as my quick save location with an auto-generated title (Antinote-year-month-day hour-minute-seconds). Searching for <code>file:Antinote</code> brings up only these notes, as a type of inbox for me to process. Once they‚Äôre renamed they no longer appear in the search results.</p>
<p>Next, with help from Johnson (Antinote‚Äôs developer, who reached out after reading this review), I was able to get Antinote to append directly to my One Big Text File. Happy days!!</p>
<p>Here‚Äôs the custom <span class="small-caps">URL</span> I‚Äôm using to append text to my vault, titled @PlainText25, and top-level file, titled <span class="small-caps">OBTF</span>:</p>
<p><code>obsidian://new?vault=@PlainText25&amp;name=OBTF&amp;append=true&amp;silent=true&amp;content={DATE}%20{CONTENT}</code></p>
<p>Note that if you want spaces, as I did between the date and content of the note, you‚Äôll need to replace them with <code>%20</code>, which I‚Äôve just learned are known as <span class="small-caps">URL</span> encoded symbols.</p>
<p>Antinote doesn‚Äôt give me all of Drafts‚Äô options when it comes to formatting text, but it‚Äôs more than enough for adding to a daily note. And simplicity is the name of the game, here. <span class="small-caps">‚å•A</span> to activate the app, start typing, then <span class="small-caps">‚åòS</span> to send the text to Obsidian. That‚Äôs what I call a smooth workflow.</p>
<h3 id="antinote-alternatives">Antinote alternatives</h3>
<p><a href="https://apps.apple.com/us/app/actions-for-obsidian/id1659667937" target="_blank">Actions for Obsidian</a> and <a href="https://forums.getdrafts.com/t/using-obsidian-with-drafts/11221" target="_blank">Drafts</a> can quickly capture and send text to Obsidian. Both require some fiddly setting up, and neither can do calculations that I‚Äôm aware of.</p>
<p>While Apple Math Notes can do similar calculations to Antinote, both can do things the other cannot. Apple Notes are also notoriously difficult to share with other apps. No plain text considerations here. You can start using calculations in Apple Notes right away, or open a new Math Note via the stock Mac Calculator app with the <span class="small-caps">‚å•‚åòM</span> shortcut.</p>
<p>SideNotes is great for persistent notes you need to access while in other apps. It has support for images, and shortcuts to apps, which Antinote lacks. SideNotes can‚Äôt do calculations, however, and its complexity, though restrained, makes it take up more mental bandwidth than Antinote. There are export options, but no direct link between SideNotes and Obsidian.</p>
<p>Calca, Numi, and Soulver look like a okay mix of notes and calculator. They can export to plain text, which is good for moving work between apps, but they‚Äôre more complex than I need or want a scratchpad to be.</p>
<p>If you‚Äôre thinking, Hey! there are other Mac apps that can bring text into Obsidian! you‚Äôre right, but I‚Äôm yet to see one with Antinote‚Äôs unique set of features, price, <em>and</em> simplicity.</p>
<h3 id="first-prize-to-antinote-for-overall-features-and-ease-of-use">First prize to Antinote for overall features and ease of use</h3>
<p>Even if all you wanted was a ready scratchpad for an affordable one-off price, Antinote is a good choice. The plain text vibe and calculation‚Ää/‚Ääconversion abilities are a nice bonus.</p>
<p><a href="https://ellanew.com/ptpl/152-2025-04-14-append-obtf-to-craft-a-dashboard">Appending (or prepending, if that‚Äôs your jive)</a>&nbsp;to a specific note in Obsidian is fantastic: it‚Äôs more like the filling in the sandwich than the icing on the cake.</p>
